1.
ifconfig: Configure and display network interfaces.
2.
ip: Show/manipulate routing, devices, policy routing, and tunnels.
3.
ping: Test the reachability of a host on an IP network.
4.
traceroute: Display the route packets take to a network host.
5.
netstat: Network statistics(netstat-s), including connections, routing tables(netstat-r), and interface statistics.
6.
ss: Utility to investigate sockets.
7.
ss-t: display TCP sockets
8.
ss-u: display UDP sockets.
9.
ss-lt: list all listening TCP connections
10.
nslookup: querying the DNS to obtain domain name or any other specific DNS record.
11.
dig: DNS lookup utility.(finds info for DNS lookups)
12.
host: DNS lookup utility.(command resolves IP addresses into domain names and viceversa).
13.
arp: Manipulate the system ARP (Address Resolution Protocol)cache.
14.
route: Show/manipulate the IP routing table.
15.
iwconfig: Configure wireless network interfaces.
16.
nmcli: Command-line client for NetworkManager.
17.
nmap: Network exploration tool and security/port scanner.
18.
tcpdump: Command-line packet analyzer.
19.
wireshark: Network protocol analyzer.
20.
curl: Transfer data from or to a server.
21.
wget: Non-interactive network downloader.
22.
Ttracepath: command is used to trace the path to a network host, similar to traceroute, but it does not require superuser privileges and has fewer options. ftp: File Transfer Protocol client.
23.
scp: Secure copy (remote file copy program).
24.
ssh: OpenSSH SSH client (remote login program).
25.
telnet: User interface to the TELNET protocol.
26.
iptables: Administration tool for IPv4 packet filtering and NAT.
27.
ufw: Uncomplicated Firewall, a frontend for iptables.
28.
fail2ban: Ban IPs that show malicious signs.
